Preheat your #oven{} to 220°C/200°C fan/gas mark 7. Chop the @potatoes{450%g} lengthways into 1cm slices, then chop into 1cm wide chips (no need to peel).

Pop the chips onto a #large baking tray{}. Drizzle with @oil, sprinkle over the @black sesame seeds{5%g}, season with @salt{} and @pepper, then toss to coat. Spread out in a single layer.

> TIP: Use two baking trays if necessary.

When the oven is hot, bake on the top shelf until golden, ~{25-30%minutes}. Turn halfway through.

Meanwhile, trim and peel the @carrot{1}(trimmed and peeled). Use the #peeler{} to peel long ribbons down the length of the carrot, stopping at the core.

In a #large bowl{}, combine the @rice vinegar{15%ml}, a drizzle of @oil, a pinch of @salt and the @sugar{1%tsp} for the dressing. Set aside your dressing for now.

While the chips cook, peel and grate the @garlic cloves{2}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}).

In a large bowl, combine the garlic, the @panko breadcrumbs{10%g} and the @salt{1/4%tsp} and @water{2%tbsp} for the breadcrumbs, then add the @British beef mince{240%g}.

Season with @pepper and mix together with your hands. Roll into evenly-sized balls, 5 per person.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw mince.

Pop the meatballs onto another large baking tray.

Bake on the middle shelf until browned on the outside and cooked through, ~{12-15%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: The meatballs are cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Once the meatballs are cooked, remove the tray from the oven.

Drain and discard the fat, then drizzle over the @gochujang paste{50%g} and @honey{15%g}. Carefully turn the meatballs to coat them in the gochujang glaze.

> TIP: If your honey has hardened, pop it in a bowl of hot water for 1 min.

When everything's ready, add the @baby leaf mix{50%g} and the carrot ribbons to the bowl of dressing. Toss together.

Share the gochujang meatballs between your plates, spooning over any remaining glaze from the tray.

Serve with the chips and salad alongside. Enjoy!